while we're talking about the law.

00:14:21.260 --> 00:14:25.860
One of them is that the ADA
is an anti-discrimination law.

00:14:27.540 --> 00:14:32.460
Its foundation is you can't discriminate
against disabled people.

00:14:32.620 --> 00:14:36.740
Second, it's a law
that requires effective communication.

00:14:37.540 --> 00:14:40.340
When we're talking about the web,
inaccessibility,

00:14:40.500 --> 00:14:44.500
of course discriminates,
because people who have disabilities

00:14:44.620 --> 00:14:48.100
can't participate
in all these other things we talked about.

00:14:48.260 --> 00:14:53.460
Effective communication,
what is web and technology about?

00:14:53.580 --> 00:14:55.100
It's about communicating.

00:14:55.220 --> 00:14:59.780
That is why, even though the ADA
was passed over 30 years ago,

00:14:59.940 --> 00:15:04.820
since almost the very beginning,
the law has recognized

00:15:05.060 --> 00:15:09.140
that the ADA applies
to the digital space.

00:15:09.340 --> 00:15:11.180
I don't really have time to do this,

00:15:11.300 --> 00:15:16.220
but I just love this quote
from 1996, 1996,

00:15:16.460 --> 00:15:22.060
where someone asked Senator
Tom Harkin in the United States

00:15:22.220 --> 00:15:25.300
about the ADA and digital.

00:15:28.380 --> 00:15:32.300
Someone asked Tom Harkin,
and Tom Harkin asked the Department of Justice,

00:15:32.460 --> 00:15:33.700
and the Department of Justice,

00:15:33.940 --> 00:15:38.460
which is the administrative agency
in charge of the ADA primarily,

00:15:38.940 --> 00:15:40.660
the Department of Justice said,

00:15:40.860 --> 00:15:44.700
"Covered entities
under the ADA are required

00:15:44.860 --> 00:15:48.220
to provide effective communication," in 1996.

00:15:48.380 --> 00:15:52.860
Regardless of whether
they generally communicate through print media,

00:15:53.020 --> 00:15:57.860
audio media, or computerized media,
such as the internet,

00:15:58.300 --> 00:16:03.700
covered entities that use the internet
for communications about programs,

00:16:03.860 --> 00:16:08.340
goods, or services, must be prepared
to offer those communications

00:16:08.500 --> 00:16:10.180
through accessible means as well.

00:16:10.340 --> 00:16:12.220
Since 1996.

00:16:12.340 --> 00:16:15.620
This is why the ADA,
even without regulations,

00:16:15.740 --> 00:16:18.940
has been such a strong proponent for accessibility.

00:16:19.140 --> 00:16:21.380
We have Section 504 and 508.

00:16:21.500 --> 00:16:22.980
We can also put that in the pocket.

00:16:23.100 --> 00:16:26.980
Section 504 is just about
federal government's going to spend money.

00:16:27.420 --> 00:16:31.420
It can't give money to organizations
that discriminate against disabled people.

00:16:31.580 --> 00:16:34.740
Section 508, federal government's
going to buy things,

00:16:34.900 --> 00:16:36.420
it has to buy accessible.

00:16:36.580 --> 00:16:39.260
That's why 508 is basically
a procurement law

00:16:39.420 --> 00:16:42.500
as well as a law that protects
the rights of disabled people

00:16:42.660 --> 00:16:45.700
to work in the federal government
with accessible technology.

00:16:45.900 --> 00:16:48.740
The Communication Video Accessibility Act

00:16:48.900 --> 00:16:50.860
and the Federal Communications Commission,

00:16:51.020 --> 00:16:55.220
that's about captioning
and audio description.

00:16:55.380 --> 00:16:56.780
There's lots of rules about that,

00:16:56.900 --> 00:16:58.340
but again, the bottom line is,

00:16:58.820 --> 00:17:03.940
are disabled people going to be able
to participate in communication technology?

00:17:04.140 --> 00:17:07.100
Or are they going to be excluded
on the other side of the bridge?

00:17:07.260 --> 00:17:10.460
The Air Carriers Access Act,
special law for airlines,

00:17:10.620 --> 00:17:14.580
also requires accessible websites
as well as kiosks.

00:17:14.780 --> 00:17:17.220
The Affordable Care Act, the ACA,

00:17:17.420 --> 00:17:24.300
Section 1557 is about accessibility
in health care technology

00:17:24.500 --> 00:17:26.220
covered by the Affordable Care Act.

00:17:26.420 --> 00:17:30.620
That's the big framework
of existing federal laws and regulations.

00:17:30.820 --> 00:17:32.580
For each law, there's a lot of regulations.

00:17:32.740 --> 00:17:34.540
I don't have time to get into it.

00:17:34.740 --> 00:17:37.140
I just want to do a,
not even a deep dive,

00:17:37.260 --> 00:17:41.820
a somewhat shallow dive into
the brand new ADA Web and Mobile Rule,

00:17:41.980 --> 00:17:45.740
which just was finalized in April of this year.

00:17:47.140 --> 00:17:51.940
I use the word regulations,
sometimes in the US, they're called rules.

00:17:52.380 --> 00:17:54.980
Rules, regulations,
kind of the same thing.

00:17:55.140 --> 00:17:59.300
The new ADA Web
and Mobile Rule is a rule

00:17:59.420 --> 00:18:03.740
that applies to state
and local governments only.

00:18:03.900 --> 00:18:06.940
I know a lot of you work
in state and local governments.

00:18:07.060 --> 00:18:08.420
It's not just the state or the city.

00:18:08.580 --> 00:18:11.020
It's any program of states and cities.

00:18:11.180 --> 00:18:14.180
I put up a few pictures here
of a county jail

00:18:14.300 --> 00:18:17.180
or a state university
or my hometown library,

00:18:17.340 --> 00:18:18.660
the Berkeley Public Library,

00:18:18.820 --> 00:18:22.220
a park system where I have
a picture here of someone

00:18:22.340 --> 00:18:24.580
in a power wheelchair on an accessible path,

00:18:24.780 --> 00:18:27.420
so all state and local governments.

00:18:27.500 --> 00:18:30.860
People often ask me,
"Is it going to apply to private sector next?"

00:18:31.500 --> 00:18:35.140
It took 14 years
to get these regulations

00:18:35.260 --> 00:18:37.620
and the whole history of it
you can read about on my website.

00:18:37.780 --> 00:18:41.060
The fact they did state
and local government doesn't mean,

00:18:41.260 --> 00:18:44.220
oh, tomorrow they're going
to do private sector.

00:18:44.340 --> 00:18:47.900
However, it does mean
that we got that out of the way,

00:18:48.100 --> 00:18:49.900
we can now focus on private sector.

00:18:50.060 --> 00:18:55.500
The standard is Web Content
Accessibility Guidelines 2.1 AA.

00:18:55.700 --> 00:18:59.420
The timeframe depends
on the size of the state

00:18:59.540 --> 00:19:01.300
or local government organization.

00:19:01.460 --> 00:19:08.700
If it's over 49,999 people,
basically if it's 50,000 people or more,

00:19:08.860 --> 00:19:12.380
then the deadline is April 2026.

00:19:12.620 --> 00:19:19.940
If it's less than that,
if it's a smaller organization, it's April 2027.

00:19:20.140 --> 00:19:22.700
Recognizing that it takes time
to do these things.

00:19:22.900 --> 00:19:26.660
It's important to remember in the timeframe
that the ADA is not suspended.

00:19:27.180 --> 00:19:29.300
Accessibility is still required.

00:19:29.500 --> 00:19:32.860
The Department of Justice
has a very good fact sheet on this.

00:19:33.020 --> 00:19:38.220
If you look up fact sheet,
Department of Justice, Web Accessibility,

00:19:38.340 --> 00:19:42.020
State and Local Government,
you can do that on my website

00:19:42.180 --> 00:19:44.780
or do it on Google,
you get the fact sheet.

00:19:45.300 --> 00:19:47.860
That has all the details
that they say in there.

00:19:48.060 --> 00:19:49.300
The ADA isn't suspended.

00:19:49.500 --> 00:19:51.300
Just recently in the past year,

00:19:51.500 --> 00:19:53.740
the Department
of Justice did a settlement

00:19:53.900 --> 00:19:57.340
with the whole state of Oklahoma
because their mobile app

00:19:57.500 --> 00:20:00.940
that allowed you to put your ID
onto the app wasn't accessible.

00:20:01.100 --> 00:20:04.980
ADA is still chugging along
while these regulations come into play.

00:20:05.100 --> 00:20:06.900
What's covered?

00:20:07.060 --> 00:20:08.580
It's web and mobile only.

00:20:08.740 --> 00:20:10.020
It doesn't apply to anything else.

00:20:10.220 --> 00:20:12.540
Pretty much everything on web and mobile.

00:20:12.660 --> 00:20:15.380
A really important thing
that they call out is,

00:20:16.660 --> 00:20:19.900
if you're a library and you say
you're buying something for your website,

00:20:20.060 --> 00:20:21.940
or you're hiring a third-party developer,

00:20:23.100 --> 00:20:26.620
the state and local government agency
is still responsible.

00:20:26.740 --> 00:20:29.220
You can't get off the hook by saying,
"I didn't build it.

00:20:29.380 --> 00:20:30.140
I hired someone to build it."

00:20:30.300 --> 00:20:31.460
There are some exceptions.

00:20:31.660 --> 00:20:33.260
They're very narrowly drawn.

00:20:33.340 --> 00:20:36.060
These are all in the fact sheet.

00:20:36.180 --> 00:20:40.500
Just one quick example
is social media is covered.

00:20:42.340 --> 00:20:46.500
There's no requirement to go back
and make old social media posts accessible.

00:20:46.700 --> 00:20:51.860
There's no requirement also to go back
and make individual documents.

00:20:51.980 --> 00:20:56.340
They particularly call out
like word processing documents,

00:20:56.500 --> 00:21:00.500
PDFs, spreadsheets,
those kind of static documents,

00:21:00.620 --> 00:21:04.620
no need to go back,
but still, the ADA still applies.

00:21:04.780 --> 00:21:07.660
If you're an agency,
you need to have a plan in place

00:21:07.820 --> 00:21:10.740
to make particular things
that might be in the exceptions,

00:21:10.860 --> 00:21:12.180
to make them accessible too.

00:21:12.340 --> 00:21:15.140
That's this new rule.

00:21:15.260 --> 00:21:17.140
There's a lot about it on the web.

00:21:17.260 --> 00:21:19.900
I encourage you
to take a look at it.

00:21:20.060 --> 00:21:24.060
Beyond regulation,
the United States federal government

00:21:24.260 --> 00:21:26.220
can do things that explain the law.

00:21:26.380 --> 00:21:30.860
I have a picture here
to represent telehealth.

00:21:31.020 --> 00:21:32.420
It's a Black medical professional.

00:21:32.580 --> 00:21:33.900
She's writing notes,

00:21:33.980 --> 00:21:37.020
